# ============================================================================
# Rule 16 - Repository Governance Standards
# ============================================================================

## Purpose

Protect the repository architecture.

The repository is a long-term product.

Every new file, package, module, service and dependency must have
a clearly defined owner.

Never add code simply because it compiles.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Repository Philosophy

Business Capability

↓

Bounded Context

↓

Microservice

↓

Module

↓

Package

↓

Class

Never reverse this order.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Repository Layout

The repository is organized into

common/

services/

plugins/

infrastructure/

docs/

monitoring/

kubernetes/

scripts/

tools/

.cursor/

Never introduce top-level folders without architectural approval.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Module Ownership

Every module

Has exactly one owner.

Examples

common-core

Platform

Lead Service

Lead Domain

Workflow Service

Workflow Domain

Real Estate Plugin

Real Estate Domain

Never create shared ownership.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Business Logic

Business logic belongs only inside

Business Services

or

Industry Plugins

Never place business logic inside

common-*

SDKs

Utilities

Infrastructure

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Common Modules

Allowed

common-core

common-events

common-contracts

common-security

common-observability

common-testing

common-clients

Never create

common-utils

common-helper

shared-business

misc

global

These become dumping grounds.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# What Belongs In Common

Allowed

Annotations

Exceptions

Base Classes

Utilities

DTO Contracts

Events

Security

Observability

Validation

Constants

Never

Lead

Customer

Property

Workflow Rules

Repositories

Business Services

Domain Models

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Service Ownership

Every business capability belongs to one service.

Example

Lead

↓

Lead Service

Customer

↓

Customer Service

Conversation

↓

Conversation Service

Billing

↓

Billing Service

AI

↓

AI Service

Never duplicate ownership.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Plugin Ownership

Industry-specific functionality belongs inside plugins.

Platform Core

Must not know

Real Estate

Healthcare

Education

Insurance

Automobile

Banking

If code contains industry terminology

It probably belongs in a plugin.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# SDK Usage

Use SDKs for cross-service capabilities.

Examples

ai-sdk

workflow-sdk

notification-sdk

plugin-sdk

event-sdk

media-sdk

Never access another service implementation directly.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Dependency Direction

Allowed

Service

↓

common-*

Service

↓

SDK

Service

↓

REST Contract

Service

↓

Events

Forbidden

common

↓

service

Plugin

↓

Platform internals

Service

↓

Another service implementation

Circular dependencies

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Package Structure

Every service

domain/

application/

api/

repository/

events/

integration/

security/

config/

mapper/

Never invent package structures.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Module Creation

Before creating a module ask

1. Is there an existing owner?
2. Can an existing module own this?
3. Is it reusable?
4. Is it business specific?
5. Is it platform specific?

Create a new module only when justified.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Duplicate Detection

Before generating code search for

Existing DTO

Existing Event

Existing API

Existing Mapper

Existing Entity

Existing Utility

Never duplicate functionality.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Shared Contracts

Cross-service communication

Uses

Contracts

Events

SDKs

Never share entities.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Repository Naming

Service Modules

lead-service

customer-service

workflow-service

Plugins

real-estate-plugin

education-plugin

insurance-plugin

SDKs

ai-sdk

workflow-sdk

media-sdk

Keep naming consistent.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Versioning

Every module

Must define

Version

Compatibility

Migration strategy

Breaking change policy

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Documentation

Every module contains

README.md

Purpose

Owner

Responsibilities

Dependencies

Public APIs

Events

Configuration

Deployment notes

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Architecture Decision Records

Require ADRs for

New microservice

New plugin

New shared module

New SDK

New infrastructure component

New persistence technology

Never introduce structural changes without documenting them.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Technical Debt

Reject

Temporary folders

Random utilities

Copy-paste modules

Duplicate SDKs

Unused abstractions

Anonymous TODOs

Every exception must be tracked.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Repository Metrics

Track

Module Count

Dependency Graph

Circular Dependencies

Unused Modules

Duplicate Code

Build Time

Test Coverage

Architecture Violations

Review regularly.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Review Checklist

Before approving verify

✓ Correct bounded context

✓ Correct service owner

✓ Correct module

✓ No duplicate functionality

✓ No circular dependency

✓ No business logic in common

✓ Correct SDK usage

✓ Plugin boundaries respected

✓ Documentation updated

✓ ADR required?

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Agent Decision Tree

Before generating any code ask

1. Which bounded context owns this?
2. Which microservice owns it?
3. Which Maven module owns it?
4. Which package owns it?
5. Does it belong in a plugin?
6. Should an SDK be used?
7. Does this duplicate existing code?
8. Does this introduce a new dependency?
9. Is the dependency direction correct?
10. Does this violate repository governance?

If any answer is unclear

STOP

Determine ownership before generating code.

Never generate code with ambiguous ownership.